\section{OpenTelemetry tracing}{

\code{mcplite} automatically creates one OpenTelemetry server span for every
parsed MCP request or notification that passes JSON-RPC envelope validation.
This includes initialization and notifications, ping, tool discovery and
calls, and valid unknown methods. Blank input, JSON parse failures, and
malformed JSON-RPC envelopes do not create MCP operation spans.

Tool authors do not need to call \code{otel::start_local_active_span()} for the
MCP operation or tool invocation. The server span remains active while tool
code runs, so optional tool-authored spans can become children without being
required. \code{mcplite} does not create a redundant automatic tool-execution
child span.

Provider and exporter configuration belongs to the standard \code{otel} and
\code{otelsdk} environment variables and APIs. \code{mcplite} does not add telemetry
arguments, choose an exporter, or configure a provider. With no exporter
configured, tracing is an effective no-op and MCP behavior is unchanged. A
safe stderr configuration is
\verb{OTEL_R_TRACES_EXPORTER=stderr Rscript --vanilla /absolute/path/to/server.R};
a remote exporter such as OTLP is also suitable.

\strong{Do not use a stdout or console exporter with a stdio MCP server.} Standard
output is reserved exclusively for MCP protocol messages, so telemetry
written there will corrupt the protocol stream.

Remote W3C parent context may be supplied in \code{params._meta.traceparent}, with
optional \code{params._meta.tracestate}. Malformed propagation data is ignored,
and \verb{_meta} is not passed to tool functions. By default, spans contain
selected low-cardinality operation metadata; raw requests and responses,
tool arguments and results, \verb{_meta}, trace headers, and condition messages
are not recorded as span attributes.
